I very much like this narrative for motivating the proposal:


The WWW's original design favored simplicity, decentralization, and low
coordination overhead, which enabled explosive adoption but sacrificed
stable references, built-in versioning, and native bidirectional linking.
As requirements shifted toward durability, verifiability, and
accountability, the case for Xanadu-style guarantees (persistent citation,
traceable reuse, integrity) becomes architecturally more attractive, at the
cost of the  coordination overhead the Web originally avoided.


Integrate it and write a great motivation section. For this, also pull in
2025 or 2026 examples from the popular media that demonstrate this shift.
Emphasize legal aspects a bit more than other aspects, since I have a lot
of documented experience publishing in the legal field.


